     224             : /*
     225             :    Flags/methods for returning states.
     226             : 
     227             :    The SWIG conversion methods, as ConvertPtr, return an integer
     228             :    that tells if the conversion was successful or not. And if not,
     229             :    an error code can be returned (see swigerrors.swg for the codes).
     230             : 
     231             :    Use the following macros/flags to set or process the returning
     232             :    states.
     233             : 
     234             :    In old versions of SWIG, code such as the following was usually written:
     235             : 
     236             :      if (SWIG_ConvertPtr(obj,vptr,ty.flags) != -1) {
     237             :        // success code
     238             :      } else {
     239             :        //fail code

     242             :    Now you can be more explicit:

     252             :

   15922             : /* -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   15923             :  * Type initialization:
   15924             :  * This problem is tough by the requirement that no dynamic
   15925             :  * memory is used. Also, since swig_type_info structures store pointers to
   15926             :  * swig_cast_info structures and swig_cast_info structures store pointers back
   15927             :  * to swig_type_info structures, we need some lookup code at initialization.
   15928             :  * The idea is that swig generates all the structures that are needed.
   15929             :  * The runtime then collects these partially filled structures.
   15930             :  * The SWIG_InitializeModule function takes these initial arrays out of
   15931             :  * swig_module, and does all the lookup, filling in the swig_module.types
   15932             :  * array with the correct data and linking the correct swig_cast_info
   15933             :  * structures together.
   15934             :  *
   15935             :  * The generated swig_type_info structures are assigned statically to an initial
   15936             :  * array. We just loop through that array, and handle each type individually.
   15937             :  * First we lookup if this type has been already loaded, and if so, use the
   15938             :  * loaded structure instead of the generated one. Then we have to fill in the
   15939             :  * cast linked list. The cast data is initially stored in something like a
   15940             :  * two-dimensional array. Each row corresponds to a type (there are the same
   15941             :  * number of rows as there are in the swig_type_initial array). Each entry in
   15942             :  * a column is one of the swig_cast_info structures for that type.
   15943             :  * The cast_initial array is actually an array of arrays, because each row has
   15944             :  * a variable number of columns. So to actually build the cast linked list,
   15945             :  * we find the array of casts associated with the type, and loop through it
   15946             :  * adding the casts to the list. The one last trick we need to do is making
   15947             :  * sure the type pointer in the swig_cast_info struct is correct.
   15948             :  *
   15949             :  * First off, we lookup the cast->type name to see if it is already loaded.
   15950             :  * There are three cases to handle:
   15951             :  *  1) If the cast->type has already been loaded AND the type we are adding
   15952             :  *     casting info to has not been loaded (it is in this module), THEN we
   15953             :  *     replace the cast->type pointer with the type pointer that has already
   15954             :  *     been loaded.
   15955             :  *  2) If BOTH types (the one we are adding casting info to, and the
   15956             :  *     cast->type) are loaded, THEN the cast info has already been loaded by
   15957             :  *     the previous module so we just ignore it.
   15958             :  *  3) Finally, if cast->type has not already been loaded, then we add that
   15959             :  *     swig_cast_info to the linked list (because the cast->type) pointer will
   15960             :  *     be correct.
   15961             :  * ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
